2. How many variables are in the original `Batting` dataset? Name three or four of them and say what they represent. 

* There are 22 variables in the `Batting` dataset. Some of these variables include: `G` the number of games in which a player played, `HR` homeeruns, `SB` stolen bases and `SO` strikeouts. 



3. What variables (columns) are in the `batters` dataset that section 3.6 creates from the `Batting` dataset?

* In the `batters` dataset that was created in section 3.6, there are 3 variables (columns). These are `playerID`, `performance`, and `n`. 




4. What does each row of `batters` represent?

* Each different row of `batters` represents a different batter based off of their `playerID`.




5. Take the second code chunk in section 3.6 and remove the line that drops rows with n less than or equal to 100.  show the resulting code and the new plot you get. 


```{r, echo: false, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE}
library(dplyr)
library(tidyverse)
library(nycflights13)
batters <- Lahman::Batting |> 
  group_by(playerID) |> 
  summarize(
    performance = sum(H, na.rm = TRUE) / sum(AB, na.rm = TRUE),
    n = sum(AB, na.rm = TRUE)
  )


batters |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = n, y = performance)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 1 / 10) + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)
```


6. Let's figure out what the `alpha` argument does. Modify the second code chunk in Section 3.6 by removing the `alpha` argument so that there is nothing inside the parentheses of `geom_point`. Show the resulting code and the new plot you get. Based on this and on the results of ?alpha, what does `alpha` control about the plot? 

```{r}
batters |> 
  filter(n > 100) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = n, y = performance)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)
```
* The `alpha` argument changes the level of translucence of the points on the `ggplot()`. A smaller `alpha` value will result in more translucent points, whereas a larger `alpha` value, or one equal to 1 will give the most opaque points. 




7. Adjust the second code chunk in Section 3.6 to give the plot more formal and informative axis labels, such as "Batting Average" for the vertical axis and "Times at Bat" on the horizontal axis. 

```{r}
batters |> 
  filter(n > 100) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = n, y = performance)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 1 / 10) + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE) +
  labs(x="Times at Bat", y="Batting Average")
```



